node.text:
Video by @rubensalgadoescudero / Thomas Benedix is one half of the DJ duo Pan-Pot. On Aug. 28 he played a live stream to fans from his living room with his wife, Merelinde, and two children dancing along. During normal times Pan-Pot will play in festivals in front of around 20,000 fans. Due to the pandemic they, along with all musicians, have had to adapt and find an alternative way to meet their audience.

Follow me @rubensalgadoescudero to see more of the world through my lens. The above video was taken in Berlin, Germany on assignment with @natgeo documenting the electronic music scene and how it is and has adapted to the changes we’ve all felt since early 2019.

#berlin #panpot #electronicmusic #techno #berlinreboot

node.text:
Photo by Caitlin O’Hara @caitlin_oh / Rivko Knox, 83, collects signatures for the Stop Dark Money petition during the March On for Voting Rights event in Phoenix on August 28.

Knox, who was a member of the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee in the 1960s, has been organizing for the anti-war and civil rights movements since she was in her 20s. “I’m an intellectual pessimist but an operational optimist. Sometimes I feel like, what’s the use? But then I’ll go out and collect signatures or march. What else can we do?”

node.text:
Photo by @nina_berman / Terry G. Collins (left), 73, and Hezekiah Jackson, 65, pose for a portrait at the March On for Voting Rights rally in Washington, D.C., on Saturday.

They arrived yesterday from Birmingham, Alabama. “We’ve come to D.C. a number of times,” Collins said. “We both grew up in Birmingham. We remember the church bombing, and I was a part of the march that happened in Birmingham for civil rights in 1963, and we are still here.

“We are part of the Urban Solutions Progress Network. It’s a local civil society organization working with a lot of youth over the years. We go wherever the action is. Our hope for today is that the Congress will realize that this country will be what it’s supposed to be. It’s supposed to stand for equal rights and for anyone who is a citizen to be able to vote. We want the millennials to understand that we have unfinished business.”

node.text:
Photo and video by @katieorlinsky / Johnny Boline holds his rifle and a caribou antler shed in the Barren Lands in Northwest Territories, Canada. Johnny has spent all summer working as the bear monitor at the Ekwǫ̀ Nàxoèhdee K’è: Boots on the Ground caribou monitoring camp. It was pretty windy but you can listen to him talking about his job, while he takes a break to pick cloud berries, in the video clip. 

The Tłı̨chǫ people have depended on and co-existed with caribou for thousands of years. They have witnessed, and felt the greatest impact, of Canada’s Bathurst Caribou herd’s shocking decline from over 400,000 in 1986 to less than 9,000 today. In 2015, the Tłı̨chǫ government instituted a caribou hunting ban, and in 2016, they began the groundbreaking Ekwǫ̀ Nàxoèhdee K’è: Boots on the Ground caribou monitoring program.

node.text: Photo of @Lynseyaddario / I am currently on assignment covering the work of #CALFIRE on the Dixie fire at the Butte Lake Campground in the Lassen National forest, August 26, 2021. Photo by @CALFIRE photographer Robert Foxworthy #wildfires #dixiefire #lynseyaddario

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Nat Geo in the Field on August 26, 2021. May be an image of 1 person.

node.text: Photo by @lynseyaddario / We stop to get an update on the Dixie fire from CALFIRE Engineer, David Carpenter, 32, as it approaches our location near Highway 44 in the Lassen National Forest, north of Lake Almanor, California, August 25, 2021.  The Dixie fire, which has already burned nearly 750,000 acres, is the second largest fire in California history. Currently there are nearly 5000 firefighters assigned to fight the Dixie fire, which is roughly 45% contained. On assignment for @natgeo #Dixiefire #wildfires #climatechange @CALFIRE #lynseyaddario

Video/Photos by @dguttenfelder 
Kayaking and exploring the 21 Apostle Islands / Wenabozho Ominisan of Lake Superior’s Apostle Islands National Lakeshore. Have a look at our stories for more behind the scenes of this @natgeointhefield  NatGeo assignment. 
1- Honeymoon rock along the shoreline of Basswood Island
2- A faded map of Lake Superior on a Sand Island historic district bedroom.
3- Open water crossing from Bear Island to Devils Island 
4- Full moon where we camped on Stockton Island’s Quarry Bay.

node.text:
Video by @leeannolwage / We have arrived. After traveling 1600 miles on some of the dustiest and most beautiful roads through South Africa and Namibia we begin our assignment on Alzheimer’s and dementia among indigenous communities in Namibia. As we approach September which is Alzheimer’s Awareness Month follow along as we explore how Alzheimer’s and dementia are perceived and treated in rural Namibia.

#alzheimers #dementia #namibia

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Nat Geo in the Field in Siberia. May be an image of one or more people and outdoors.

node.text:
Photo by @emileducke / Siberia’s massive wildfires are unlocking extreme carbon pollution, releasing nearly 800 million tons of carbon dioxide since June. That is roughly as much as Germany does in a year.

Terentiy Ignatyev, 64, works with his family members in the fields around Argas as smoke hangs overhead.

Taken while on assignment for @natgeo for a story on the forest fires raging in the Yakutia (Sakha Republic) region of Russia this year.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Nat Geo in the Field in Siberia. May be an image of one or more people, people standing, grass and nature.

node.text:
Photo by @emileducke / Varvara Ignatyeva, 30, (left), Konstantin Ignatyev, 27, (center), and Boris Ignatyev, 37, (right) collect hay for the family cows around the village of Argas, in far northeastern Siberia, as smoke from local wildfires hangs overhead.

Taken while on assignment for @natgeo for a story on the forest fires raging in the Yakutia (Sakha Republic) region of Russia this year.
